SIMPLE: swink
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Swink
<hw>Swink</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.</pos> <conjf>Swank</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>, <conjf>Swonk</conjf> <pr>(<?/)</pr>; <pos>p. p.</pos> <conjf>Swonken</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Swinking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>swincan</ets>, akin to <ets>swingan</ets>. See <er>Swing</er>.]</ety> <def>To labor; to toil; to salve.</def> <mark>[Obs. or Archaic]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Or <qex>swink</qex> with his hands and labor.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For which men <qex>swink</qex> and sweat incessantly.</q> <rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>swinking</qex> crowd at every stroke pant ⟦ldquo⟧Ho.⟦rdquo⟧</q> <rj><qau>Sir Samuel Freguson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Swink</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Swink
<hw>Swink</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cause to toil or drudge; to tire or exhaust with labor.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And the <qex>swinked</qex> hedger at his supper sat.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To acquire by labor.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Piers Plowman.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To devour all that others <qex>swink</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Swink</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Swink
<hw>Swink</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[As. <ets>swinc</ets>, ge<ets>swinc</ets>.]</ety> <def>Labor; toil; drudgery.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>  <rj><au>Chaucer. Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Swinker</ent>⟦br⟧
